        <link rel="schema.DC" href="https://purl.org/DC/elements/1.0/" /><meta name="citation_journal_title" content="RadioGraphics" /><meta name="dc.Title" content="Imaging of Oncologic Emergencies: What Every Radiologist Should Know" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Venkata S.  Katabathina" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Carlos S.  Restrepo" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Sonia L.  Betancourt Cuellar" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Roy F.  Riascos" /><meta name="dc.Creator" content="Christine O.  Menias" /><meta name="dc.Description" content="The pathophysiology and imaging findings of select oncologic emergencies are reviewed, with emphasis on those in which radiologists play a critical role in timely diagnosis and thus have a signific..." /><meta name="Description" content="The pathophysiology and imaging findings of select oncologic emergencies are reviewed, with emphasis on those in which radiologists play a critical role in timely diagnosis and thus have a signific..." /><meta name="dc.Description" content="Acute life-threatening conditions in oncology patients may develop either because of underlying malignancy or as a complication from treatment. Oncologic emergencies can be categorized as metabolic..." /><meta name="Description" content="Acute life-threatening conditions in oncology patients may develop either because of underlying malignancy or as a complication from treatment. Oncologic emergencies can be categorized as metabolic..." /><meta name="dc.Publisher" content="Radiological Society of North America" /><meta name="dc.Date" scheme="WTN8601" content="2013-10-01" /><meta name="dc.Type" content="research-article" /><meta name="dc.Format" content="text/HTML" /><meta name="dc.Identifier" scheme="publisher-id" content="135508" /><meta name="dc.Identifier" scheme="doi" content="10.1148/rg.336135508" /><meta name="dc.Source" content="https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.336135508" /><meta name="dc.Language" content="EN" /><meta name="dc.Coverage" cont