</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Acute life-threatening conditions in oncology patients may develop either because of underlying malignancy or as a complication from treatment. Oncologic emergencies can be categorized as metabolic, hematologic, and structural conditions. Metabolic and hematologic emergencies are mainly diagnosed on the basis of clinical and laboratory findings. Structural pathologic conditions that result in bleeding, mechanical compression, or obstruction to the hollow organs, such as the trachea and bowel loops, may first be suspected because of clinical findings, including decreasing hematocrit levels, difficulty in breathing, and abdominal pain; however, performance of imaging studies is critical for timely diagnosis and management. Life-threatening conditions of the central nervous system (such as cerebral herniation, carcinomatous meningitis, and spinal cord compression), thoracic emergent conditions (such as central airway obstruction, esophagorespiratory fistula, massive hemoptysis, pulmonary embolism, superior vena cava syndrome, and pericardial tamponade), and abdominopelvic emergencies (such as uncontrolled intraabdominal hemorrhage, bowel obstruction, intestinal perforation, bowel ischemia, intussusception, and urinary tract obstruction) can be definitively diagnosed on the basis of projectional or cross-sectional imaging findings in appropriate clinical scenarios. Select emergent conditions in cancer patients related to chemotherapy and radiation treatment, as well as iatrogenic emergencies secondary to either surgery or placement of central venous catheters, may also demonstrate characteristic findings at imaging studies. In addition, interventional procedures are of great help in the treatment of acute superior vena cava syndrome, massive hemoptysis, and uncontrolled intraabdominal hemorrhage. Radiologists should be aware of these select, “not to be missed” imaging findings of oncologic emergencies to make an accurate, timely diagnosis and provide appropriate patient care.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2013</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.336135508">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.336135508">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig01a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig01a.jpeg" height="695" width="1120" aria-labelledby="fig01a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span> Cerebral herniation. <b>(a)</b> Drawing of the coronal view of the brain shows common types of cerebral herniation in cancer patients. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial T2-weighted <b>(b)</b> and coronal T1-weighted <b>(c)</b> MR images in a 57-year-old man with known malignant melanoma demonstrate a metastatic deposit in the right parietal lobe (arrow) with perilesional vasogenic edema, midline shift, and subfalcine herniation (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig01a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig01b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig01b.jpeg" height="693" width="662" aria-labelledby="fig01b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span> Cerebral herniation. <b>(a)</b> Drawing of the coronal view of the brain shows common types of cerebral herniation in cancer patients. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial T2-weighted <b>(b)</b> and coronal T1-weighted <b>(c)</b> MR images in a 57-year-old man with known malignant melanoma demonstrate a metastatic deposit in the right parietal lobe (arrow) with perilesional vasogenic edema, midline shift, and subfalcine herniation (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig01b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig01c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig01c.jpeg" height="693" width="663" aria-labelledby="fig01c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span> Cerebral herniation. <b>(a)</b> Drawing of the coronal view of the brain shows common types of cerebral herniation in cancer patients. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial T2-weighted <b>(b)</b> and coronal T1-weighted <b>(c)</b> MR images in a 57-year-old man with known malignant melanoma demonstrate a metastatic deposit in the right parietal lobe (arrow) with perilesional vasogenic edema, midline shift, and subfalcine herniation (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig01c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig02" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig02.jpeg" height="854" width="736" aria-labelledby="fig02" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span> Carcinomatous meningitis in a 57-year-old woman with breast carcinoma who came to the emergency department because of altered consciousness. Axial contrast-enhanced MR image demonstrates irregular enhancement (arrows) of the dura mater, sulci, ventricles, and basal cisterns, findings suggestive of carcinomatous meningitis. The diagnosis was confirmed by means of cerebrospinal fluid cytologic analysis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig02">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig03" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig03.jpeg" height="854" width="739" aria-labelledby="fig03" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span> Carcinomatous meningitis in a 63-year-old man with a history of treated non-Hodgkin lymphoma. Axial contrast-enhanced MR image depicts irregular thickening and enhancement of the dura mater and sulci (arrows). The diagnosis of lymphoma was proved by results of meningeal biopsy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig03">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig04a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig04a.jpeg" height="744" width="864" aria-labelledby="fig04a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> Malignant spinal cord compression of the thoracic spine in a 42-year-old man with lung carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT image obtained at the level of the T11 vertebral body shows lytic metastases with prevertebral soft-tissue swelling (arrows) without obvious narrowing of the spinal canal. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal T2-weighted MR image depicts loss of vertebral body height, with retropulsion that causes spinal cord compression (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig04a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig04b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig04b.jpeg" height="744" width="711" aria-labelledby="fig04b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> Malignant spinal cord compression of the thoracic spine in a 42-year-old man with lung carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT image obtained at the level of the T11 vertebral body shows lytic metastases with prevertebral soft-tissue swelling (arrows) without obvious narrowing of the spinal canal. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal T2-weighted MR image depicts loss of vertebral body height, with retropulsion that causes spinal cord compression (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig04b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig05a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig05a.jpeg" height="672" width="666" aria-labelledby="fig05a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> Tracheal chondroma in a 47-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Conventional tomographic image of the lower neck and upper chest shows a radiopaque mass in the region of the trachea (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial unenhanced CT image demonstrates a calcified mass arising from the tracheal wall that partially obstructs the trachea (arrowhead). The mass was proved to be a chondroma after surgical resection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig05a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig05b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig05b.jpeg" height="672" width="909" aria-labelledby="fig05b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> Tracheal chondroma in a 47-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Conventional tomographic image of the lower neck and upper chest shows a radiopaque mass in the region of the trachea (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial unenhanced CT image demonstrates a calcified mass arising from the tracheal wall that partially obstructs the trachea (arrowhead). The mass was proved to be a chondroma after surgical resection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig05b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig06a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig06a.jpeg" height="670" width="908" aria-labelledby="fig06a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> Small cell lung carcinoma in a 76-year-old man. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> unenhanced CT images demonstrate a large mediastinal mass (arrows) that extends into the bilateral hila, carina, and bilateral main bronchi and causes airway obstruction (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig06a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig06b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig06b.jpeg" height="670" width="667" aria-labelledby="fig06b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> Small cell lung carcinoma in a 76-year-old man. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> unenhanced CT images demonstrate a large mediastinal mass (arrows) that extends into the bilateral hila, carina, and bilateral main bronchi and causes airway obstruction (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig06b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig07" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig07.jpeg" height="719" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig07" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span> Esophagorespiratory fistula in a 75-year-old man with known esophageal carcinoma. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image demonstrates a fistulous communication between the esophagus and the trachea (arrow) that developed after radiation therapy. An ill-defined soft-tissue thickening in the left lateral esophageal wall (arrowhead) that extends up to the fistula is seen, a finding consistent with esophageal cancer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig07">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig08" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig08.jpeg" height="642" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig08" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span> Esophagorespiratory fistula in a 68-year-old man with known carcinoma of the lung. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image depicts a large mass in the right upper lobe of the lung (arrows) with fistulous communication with the esophagus (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig08">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig09" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig09.jpeg" height="687" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig09" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span> Massive hemoptysis in a 63-year-old man with known lung carcinoma. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image demonstrates a large mass in the right lung (arrows) with a central pseudoaneurysm (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig09">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig10.jpeg" height="666" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span> Massive hemoptysis in a 58-year-old woman with known lung carcinoma. Digital subtraction angiogram of the right internal mammary artery demonstrates hypertrophy and hypervascularity (arrows), which was subsequently embolized with polyvinyl alcohol particles.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig11.jpeg" height="680" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span> Pulmonary embolism in a 60-year-old woman with known cervical carcinoma. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of the chest shows large emboli involving the right and left main pulmonary arteries (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig12.jpeg" height="867" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span> Pulmonary embolism in a 48-year-old man with a history of renal cell carcinoma of the right kidney. Curved planar reformatted CT image shows the continuity of tumor thrombus from the inferior vena cava to the right atrium, to the right ventricle, and into the left main pulmonary artery (arrowheads). Thrombus was also seen extending into the right main pulmonary artery (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig13a.jpeg" height="840" width="755" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span> SVC syndrome in a 43-year-old woman with a known small cell carcinoma of the right lung, who came to the emergency department with severe breathlessness. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT image depicts a large tumor thrombus invading into the SVC and the right atrium (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Three-dimensional volume-rendered image of the chest demonstrates extensive collateral vessels in the chest wall.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig13b.jpeg" height="840" width="720" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span> SVC syndrome in a 43-year-old woman with a known small cell carcinoma of the right lung, who came to the emergency department with severe breathlessness. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT image depicts a large tumor thrombus invading into the SVC and the right atrium (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Three-dimensional volume-rendered image of the chest demonstrates extensive collateral vessels in the chest wall.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig14a.jpeg" height="724" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span> SVC syndrome treated with stent placement. <b>(a)</b> SVC venogram obtained before treatment demonstrates a short segment of focal narrowing of the SVC at the cavoatrial junction (arrows) secondary to a right lung carcinoma (not shown). The stenosis was treated with angioplasty and stent placement. <b>(b)</b> SVC venogram obtained after stent placement shows the patent SVC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig14b.jpeg" height="724" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span> SVC syndrome treated with stent placement. <b>(a)</b> SVC venogram obtained before treatment demonstrates a short segment of focal narrowing of the SVC at the cavoatrial junction (arrows) secondary to a right lung carcinoma (not shown). The stenosis was treated with angioplasty and stent placement. <b>(b)</b> SVC venogram obtained after stent placement shows the patent SVC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig15.jpeg" height="682" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span> Pericardial tamponade in a 62-year-old man. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image depicts a large pericardial effusion (arrows) that causes severe compression and narrowing of the cardiac chambers, findings consistent with pericardial tamponade. Immediate pericardiocentesis was performed, and analysis of the fluid revealed metastases from lung carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig16.jpeg" height="694" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span> Pericardial tamponade in a 77-year-old man. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image demonstrates irregular soft-tissue thickening (arrowheads) of the pericardium that results in narrowing of the cardiac chambers. Primary pericardial rhabdomyosarcoma was diagnosed at pathologic examination.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig17a.jpeg" height="717" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span> Spontaneous hemoperitoneum secondary to rupture of a hepatocellular carcinoma in a 57-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT image demonstrates an ill-defined focal lesion in the left lobe of the liver (arrow) and a hyperattenuating hematoma in the hepatogastric space (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image depicts active extravasation of contrast material (arrowhead), a finding consistent with ongoing bleeding secondary to rupture of a hepatocellular carcinoma. In addition, diffuse infiltrating tumor involving both lobes of the liver and a portal venous thrombus (arrow) are also identified. <b>(c)</b> Left hepatic arteriogram demonstrates increased vascularity and active contrast material extravasation (arrows), which was subsequently treated with coil embolization.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig17b.jpeg" height="717" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span> Spontaneous hemoperitoneum secondary to rupture of a hepatocellular carcinoma in a 57-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT image demonstrates an ill-defined focal lesion in the left lobe of the liver (arrow) and a hyperattenuating hematoma in the hepatogastric space (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image depicts active extravasation of contrast material (arrowhead), a finding consistent with ongoing bleeding secondary to rupture of a hepatocellular carcinoma. In addition, diffuse infiltrating tumor involving both lobes of the liver and a portal venous thrombus (arrow) are also identified. <b>(c)</b> Left hepatic arteriogram demonstrates increased vascularity and active contrast material extravasation (arrows), which was subsequently treated with coil embolization.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig17c.jpeg" height="921" width="686" aria-labelledby="fig17c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17c</span> Spontaneous hemoperitoneum secondary to rupture of a hepatocellular carcinoma in a 57-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT image demonstrates an ill-defined focal lesion in the left lobe of the liver (arrow) and a hyperattenuating hematoma in the hepatogastric space (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image depicts active extravasation of contrast material (arrowhead), a finding consistent with ongoing bleeding secondary to rupture of a hepatocellular carcinoma. In addition, diffuse infiltrating tumor involving both lobes of the liver and a portal venous thrombus (arrow) are also identified. <b>(c)</b> Left hepatic arteriogram demonstrates increased vascularity and active contrast material extravasation (arrows), which was subsequently treated with coil embolization.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig17c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig18.jpeg" height="920" width="789" aria-labelledby="fig18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span> Spontaneous rupture of a hypervascular right adrenal gland metastasis in a 52-year-old man with a known history of malignant melanoma. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image demonstrates a heterogeneously enhancing right adrenal mass (arrow) with associated active contrast material extravasation (arrowhead) and hemoperitoneum, findings consistent with rupture.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig19a.jpeg" height="739" width="863" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span> Malignant large bowel obstruction in a 32-year-old man. Axial <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images depict a rectal mass (arrow) and dilated proximal colonic loops (arrowhead), findings consistent with malignant obstruction. After surgical resection, the rectal mass proved to be a rectal adenocarcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig19b.jpeg" height="739" width="712" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span> Malignant large bowel obstruction in a 32-year-old man. Axial <b>(a)</b> and sagittal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images depict a rectal mass (arrow) and dilated proximal colonic loops (arrowhead), findings consistent with malignant obstruction. After surgical resection, the rectal mass proved to be a rectal adenocarcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig20.jpeg" height="771" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig20" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20</span> Malignant small bowel obstruction in a 56-year-old woman with a known history of serous ovarian carcinoma, hysterectomy, and salpingo-oophorectomy. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image demonstrates dilated fluid-filled small bowel loops (arrows) and enhancing peritoneal nodules (arrowhead), findings consistent with peritoneal carcinomatosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig20">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig21.jpeg" height="718" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig21" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21</span> Spontaneous perforation of gastric lymphoma in a 54-year-old man. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image demonstrates irregular, diffuse wall thickening of the distal gastric body and antropyloric region of the stomach (arrows), with focal discontinuity of the anterior gastric wall and perigastric free air (arrowheads), findings consistent with perforation. Gastric lymphoma was diagnosed at pathologic examination.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig21">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig22.jpeg" height="718" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig22" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22</span> Spontaneous perforation of colonic adenocarcinoma in a 62-year-old woman with severe hematemesis. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image demonstrates irregular thickening of a segment of transverse colon (arrow), focal active contrast material extravasation (white arrowhead), and a few areas of hyperattenuation within the gastric lumen (black arrowheads) consistent with hematomas. Spontaneous perforation of colonic carcinoma into the gastric lumen was diagnosed at surgical resection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig22">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig23a.jpeg" height="592" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig23a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23a</span> Bowel ischemia in a 68-year-old woman with a known history of pancreatic adenocarcinoma who came to the emergency department with severe abdominal pain. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images obtained at two different levels show an ill-defined hypoattenuating pancreatic mass encasing the superior mesenteric vessels (arrows in <b>a</b>), as well as intramural gas that involves multiple small bowel loops and intrahepatic portal venous branches (arrowheads), findings consistent with bowel ischemia.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig23a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig23b.jpeg" height="592" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig23b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23b</span> Bowel ischemia in a 68-year-old woman with a known history of pancreatic adenocarcinoma who came to the emergency department with severe abdominal pain. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images obtained at two different levels show an ill-defined hypoattenuating pancreatic mass encasing the superior mesenteric vessels (arrows in <b>a</b>), as well as intramural gas that involves multiple small bowel loops and intrahepatic portal venous branches (arrowheads), findings consistent with bowel ischemia.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig23b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig24a.jpeg" height="592" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig24a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24a</span> Ileo-ileal intussusception resulting from an ileal gastrointestinal stromal tumor acting as the lead point in a 49-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image depicts an oval mass with central regions of fat attenuation (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Photograph of the gross pathology specimen shows a focal mass as the lead point for ileo-ileal intussusception (arrows). The mass proved to be gastrointestinal stromal tumor at pathologic analysis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig24a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig24b.jpeg" height="592" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig24b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24b</span> Ileo-ileal intussusception resulting from an ileal gastrointestinal stromal tumor acting as the lead point in a 49-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image depicts an oval mass with central regions of fat attenuation (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Photograph of the gross pathology specimen shows a focal mass as the lead point for ileo-ileal intussusception (arrows). The mass proved to be gastrointestinal stromal tumor at pathologic analysis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig24b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig25a.jpeg" height="638" width="903" aria-labelledby="fig25a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25a</span> Ileo-colic intussusception resulting from a cecal adenocarcinoma in a 53-year-old woman. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images demonstrate a sausage-shaped mass with a bowel-within-bowel appearance (arrowheads), features consistent with intussusception. Findings from surgical resection and pathologic examination confirmed the diagnosis of cecal adenocarcinoma and ileo-colic intussusception.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig25a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig25b.jpeg" height="911" width="772" aria-labelledby="fig25b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25b</span> Ileo-colic intussusception resulting from a cecal adenocarcinoma in a 53-year-old woman. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images demonstrate a sausage-shaped mass with a bowel-within-bowel appearance (arrowheads), features consistent with intussusception. Findings from surgical resection and pathologic examination confirmed the diagnosis of cecal adenocarcinoma and ileo-colic intussusception.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig25b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig26.jpeg" height="931" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig26" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26</span> Urinary tract obstruction in a 31-year-old man who came to the emergency department with severe abdominal pain. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image demonstrates moderate bilateral hydronephrosis, hypoenhancement of the right kidney (arrows), and a soft-tissue attenuation mass arising from one of the small bowel loops in the pelvis (arrowheads). The mass was causing compression on the bilateral ureters (not shown) and proved to be non-Hodgkin lymphoma at pathologic examination.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig26">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig27.jpeg" height="931" width="787" aria-labelledby="fig27" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27</span> Urinary tract obstruction in a 35-year-old man with retroperitoneal metastatic lymphadenopathy from a mixed germ cell testicular neoplasm. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image depicts a large heterogeneously enhancing retroperitoneal mass (arrows) that is causing compression and displacement of the left kidney. Moderate hydronephrosis and decreased renal parenchymal enhancement (arrowheads) are also seen; all findings are consistent with ureteric obstruction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig27">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig28.jpeg" height="949" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig28" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28</span> Chemotherapy-related thrombosis in a 72-year-old man with lung cancer in the right lung who underwent cisplatin-based treatment. Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image shows thrombi in the aortic arch and descending thoracic aorta (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig28">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig29" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig29.jpeg" height="762" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig29" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 29</span> Spontaneous intestinal perforation that developed 2 weeks after bevacizumab treatment in a 57-year-old man with known rectal carcinoma. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image demonstrates irregular rectal wall thickening (arrows) and a pelvic fluid collection that contains a few foci of air (arrowheads), findings consistent with intestinal perforation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig29">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig30" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig30.jpeg" height="762" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig30" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 30</span> Radiation-induced enteritis and bowel ischemia in a 54-year-old woman with known cervical carcinoma who underwent pelvic irradiation after hysterectomy. Axial unenhanced CT image demonstrates irregular wall thickening and intramural air that involves multiple small bowel loops (arrows), findings consistent with intestinal ischemia.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig30">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig31" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336135508/asset/images/large/135508fig31.jpeg" height="762" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig31" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 31</span> Arterial injury after right subclavian vein catheter placement in a 55-year-old man with a known history of lung carcinoma. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large hematoma with active contrast material extravasation involving the right axilla (arrows). Injury to the subclavian artery was confirmed at digital subtraction angiography (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336135508&amp;id=fig31">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div